From the fact that an extension of W by \mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}, over an arbitrary base, is always locally trivial, it follows, essentially formally, that \begin {aligned} \operatorname {Biext}^i(V,W;\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m}) &= \operatorname {Ext}^i(V,\underline {\operatorname {Hom}}(W,\mathbb {G}_\mathrm {m})) \\&= \operatorname {Ext}^i(V,W^*) \qquad \text {for }i=1,2. \end {aligned}

